  <block refid="94906bb0-2b1f-42d9-b91a-3b52038e9fdc">
    <STATIC_heading>
  <headingLevel value="subheadinga"/>
  <text>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color:#007FAD;"&gt;LOCATION AND STRUCTURE&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</text>
</STATIC_heading>
  </block>
  <block refid="e3cfae4f-4ddb-415f-9290-6ea83ba0a8ee">
    <STATIC_text>
  <text>&lt;p&gt;Label Figure 18-2.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;thyroid gland&lt;/strong&gt; [1] is composed of a right and a left lobe on either side of the &lt;strong&gt;trachea &lt;/strong&gt;[2], just below a large piece of cartilage called the &lt;strong&gt;thyroid cartilage&lt;/strong&gt; [3]. The thyroid cartilage covers the larynx and produces the prominence on the neck known in men as the “Adam’s apple.” The &lt;strong&gt;isthmus &lt;/strong&gt;[4] of the thyroid gland is a narrow strip of glandular tissue that connects the two lobes on the ventral (anterior) surface of the trachea.&lt;/p&gt;</text>
</STATIC_text>
  </block>
